Sum tibi Mercurium] He says he is the man's Mercurius, who was repre- sented in works of art as offer-ing different persons a ‘ marsupium,' bag of money, as stated on Horace, S. ii. 3. 68, “ Rejecta praeda quam praesens Mercurius fert.'’ Probably Persius had this passage in mind. He means the man would be a fool to reject the purse because he did not know how much it contained, or because it did not contain as much as he wished, and so he would be a fool to reject his ‘hereditas’ because part of the property had been spent.
